If they **retreat (却)**, the speaker is **shamed by his weakness (说者羞其弱)**;
if they **evade with words (以辞却之)**, then the speaker **is shamed by his weakness (则说)**,
while those who **lay the blame (责之者)** are **shamed by his weakness (羞其弱)**—
this **leads to the exhaustion of their strength (其势铃)** until they **must resort to arms (至於用兵)**.
A thousand **base (万贱)** may not **straighten (挠)** one **noble (贵)** who **bows (曲)**;
and those **below (在下者)** have **no means to counter (回)** them."

th.

Thus, what is precious in studying
is not merely reciting words—
it lies in grasping the body of the text,
understanding the meaning of speech."*

Pangzi said:
*"What are the Nine **Paths**?"*

Lüguanzi said:
*"First, **Dao** and virtue;
second, yin and yang;
third, laws and orders;
fourth, celestial officials;
fifth, divine omens;
sixth, arts and skills;
seventh, human nature;
eighth, tools and instruments;
ninth, military strategy."*

Pangzi said:
*"I wish to hear of the Nine **Paths**."*
